FAQ_Q_20=Should I use the stable version of Diamond or the development version?
FAQ_A_20:
  If you're interested in developing a project that should be used in production, then you should go with the stable version.<br>
  <br>
  However if you're interested in contributing to Diamond, then you should go with the development version.
;

FAQ_Q_21=How do I handle errors in Diamond?
FAQ_A_21=There are plenty of error-handling mechanisms in Diamond. Please see <a href="/docs/error-handling">this</a> for more information.

FAQ_Q_22=Are views dynamic?
FAQ_A_22:
  Views are dynamic, but statically compiled and thus if you change a view you need to recompile the whole project.<br>
  <br>
  This means that the dynamic data of views can be rendered blazingly fast.
;

FAQ_Q_23=What code can views contain?
FAQ_A_23=All D code is allowed in views, thanks to D supporting almost everything within function bodies.

FAQ_Q_24=Why did you choose to use a similar syntax to ASP.NET razor and not something else?
FAQ_A_24:
I (The core developer of Diamond) came from a background working with ASP.NET, so it was what I was familiar with.<br>
<br>
I wasn't a big fan of the syntax Diet templates in vibe.d uses and thus Diamond actually started as just an alternative template engine.
;

FAQ_Q_25=How secure is Diamond?
FAQ_A_25:
  Diamond is built with security in mind and thus there shouldn't be any major security risks in using Diamond.<br>
  <br>
  In fact there are a lot of security functionality built-in which you can use or extend to secure your applications even more.
;

FAQ_Q_26=I have found a security problem, what should I do?
FAQ_A_26:
  Depending on what it is then you should file an issue <a href="https://github.com/DiamondMVC/Diamond/issues">here</a>.<br>
  <br>
  If the security problem exists within one of Diamond's dependencies such as vibe.d, mysql-native, D runtime or Phobos, please report it to them and not us.<br>
  <br>
  Only report security issues in Diamond that are strictly related to Diamond.
;

FAQ_Q_27=Do I have to use your project structure?
FAQ_A_27:
  No, but we recommend it as some functionality does depend on it.<br>
  <br>
  You're not forced to however, but it could mean specific limits.
;

FAQ_Q_28=Does Diamond support NoSQL databases?
FAQ_A_28=Yes. Diamond has support for both Mongo and Redis.

FAQ_Q_29=Does Diamond support MySql or MariaDb?
FAQ_A_29:
  Yes. Diamond supports MySql and MariaDb through its dependency to mysql-native.<br>
  <br>
  By default there is an ORM built into Diamond that wraps around MySql/MariaDb also.<br>
  <br>
  The ORM can be extended to use any type of data and not just MySql/MariaDb however.
;

FAQ_Q_30=Does Diamond support MSSQL?
FAQ_A_30=No. There is no official support for MSSQL, but it's possible to extend Diamond and use it.

FAQ_Q_31=Can I use static files with Diamond?
FAQ_A_31=Yes, static files are supported by Diamond and you specify multiple paths that Diamond should search for static files in.

FAQ_Q_32=Can Diamond manage users, roles and permissions?
FAQ_A_32:
  Diamond has basic support for user roles and permissions, which can be used like ACL.<br>
  <br>
  You can extend the functionality however you want.
;

FAQ_Q_33=Can Diamond handle authentication?
FAQ_A_33=Diamond has authentication built-in and it can be combined with the built-in ACL functionality.

